{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608713/1958022301/0597.xml":{"full_text":"BUSY LEGISLATORS\nDixies Record\nOs Resistance\nBy DAVID KOONCE\nStar Staff Writer\nIn the almost four years since the Supreme Court's school\ndesegregation decisions, the 11 States of the resisting South have\nwritten literaliy hundreds of \u201canti-Negro\u201d laws into their law books.\nThe legal codes of these States already were heavy with statutes\nbased on Southern racial concepts. But since the school decisions,\nthere lias been more legislating in this area than in the mid-1800s.\nwhen Southerners were fashioning legal weapons to preserve slavery,\nor in the post-Reconstruction\nperiod between 1872 and IMOO.\nwhen most of the jim crow laws\nwere enacted.\nThis growing body of laws con\nsists of:\nStatutes enacted by legislatures\nto apply to the whole State or to\ndeal with special situations in in\ndividual counties.\nAmendments to State constitu\ntions.\nLocal ordinances passed by\ncounty and city governing bodies.\nOs these laws, 145 are attempts\nto delay or thwart altogether de\nsegregation of public schools, ac\ncording to \"Southern School\nNews,\" an independent reporting\nservice. Nine of these have been\ndeclared unconstitutional by the\ncourts, and one\u2014the North Caro\nlina pupil assignment law\u2014has\npassed court tests. Most, of course,\nhave not been brought before the\ncourts.\nHere is a State-by-State run\ndown of the most important racial\nlaws enacted in the South since\nthe school desegregation decisions:\nAlabama\nLike a number of other States,\nAlabama has a pupil placement\nlaw which makes desegregation\nvirtually impossible. Its legisla\nture also adopted an interposition\nresolution declaring the United\nStates Supreme Court's school de\ncisions \u201cnull and void.\u201d\nThe State constitution has been\namended to permit the legisla\nture to classify as judicial officers\nall members of the State educa\ntion board, city and county school\nboards and commissions, and all\nsuperintendents of schools, school\nofficials and school employes. The\nmotive here was to give to anyone\nwho might ever be a defendant\nin an integration case immuniza\ntion against lawsuits by putting\nthem in the same classification\nas State judges.\nIn a package of constitutional\namendments, the legislature was\ngiven authority to close, deny\nState aid to, or dispose of public\nschools facing integration, and to\nturn such school property over to\nprivate schools.\nStill another amendment au\nthorizes the legislature to abolish\nMacon County (84 per cent Ne\ngro), dividing its territory among\nadjacent counties. This was a\nmove to dilute the potentially\nlarge Negro electorate In the boun\nty where the Negro college, Tuske\ngee Institute, is located. Last year,\nthe legislature wiped out the\nboundaries of the town of Tuske\ngee and then gerrymandered its\nlifnits in a manner that left the\ngreat majority of its Negro resi\ndents living outside the town.\nTwo laws have been passed by,\nthe legislature allowing Macon\nand Marengo Counties to fire any\nteacher \u201cto promote the best in\nterest of the schools.\"\nThe city of Montgomery has\nbanned athletic contests in which\nthere are both Negro and white\nparticipants, and Birmingham,\ndespite a Supreme Court decision\nto the contrary, has re-enacted its\nordinance requiring segregation\non city buses.\nArkansas\nPrior to last year\u2019s integration\ndisorders at Little Rock, the legis\nlature set up a \u201cState Sovereignty\nCommission\u201d with broad author\nity to subpoena and examine \u201call\nrecords, books, documents and\nother papers touching upon or\nconcerning the matters and things\nabout which the commission is\nauthorized to conduct an investi\ngation.\u201d\nAll persons and organizations\npromoting school desegregation\nare required to register with the\ncommission and submit periodical\nreports to it. And in Little Rock\nand 11 other cities, ordinances\nobviously aimed at the National\nAssociation for the Advancement\nof Colored People require any\norganization to furnish to local\nofficials on demand information\non its finances, officers and mem\nbers.\nArkansas voters have approved\na constitutional amendment call\ning on the State legislature to\n\"take appropriate action and pass\nlaws opposing In every constitu\ntional manner the unconsti\ntutional desegregation decisions\nIncluding interposing the\nsovereignty of the State of\nArkansas.\nThe State also has a pupil\nassignment plan and its com\npulsory school attendance law has\nbeen amended to exempt pupils\nattending integrated classes.\nFlorida\nAmong the anti-integration\nweapons in Florida\u2019s arsenal Is a\npupil placement act, an interposi\ntion resolution, and a law pro\nviding for the automatic closing\nof any school where Federal troops\nare used in an attempt to enforce\ndesegregation.\nFlorida school officials have\nbeen authorized to ignore teach-*\nera* contracts that are in effect,\nregardless of the individual teach\ner\u2019s qualifications. This permits\nthe dropping of Negro teachers.\nOne law, which sponsors said\nprovided emergency authority to\nput down violence, authorizes the\nGovernor to cope with \"threats\nand danger\u201d by ordering \"any In\ndividual person, corporation, as\nsociation or group of persons to\ndo any act which would in his\nopinion prevent danger to life,\nlimb or property, prevent a breach\nof the peace or to refrain from\ndoing any act or thing.\u201d\nA committee of the legislature\nwas set up with broad subpoena\npowers to investigate the NAACP.\nGeorgia\nThe Georgia Legislature has\nadopted an interposition resolu\ntion. a demand for impeachment\nof the Supreme Court Justices\nwho participated in the school\ndecisions, and a memorial to de\nclare the 14th and 15th Amend\nments to the Federal Constitution\ninvalid.\nA package of five laws enacted\nin 1956 provides for the closing of\nall public schools and the conse\nquent establishment of a State\nsponsored private school system\nin the event integration becomes\ninevitable.\nAnother statute, passed in 1955.\nwould deny funds to any school j\nfacing integration, making it a\nfelony for any State, county or\ncity school official to spend tax\nmoney on integrated schools.\nAt the University of Georgia\nSchool of Law, where segregation\nis now under court attack, admis\nsion requirements announced by\nthe State Board of Regents make\nit practically impossible for a\nNegro to go any further than\nobtain an admission application.\nA 1956 law provides that any\npeace officer \"who knowingly re\nfuses or fails to attempt to enforce\nany law requiring segregation\u201d will\nlose all his retirement, disability\nand death benefits.\nAfter segregation of interstate\ntransportation was declared un\nconstitutional Georgia adopted a\nlaw requiring segregation of in\ntrastate passengers in waiting\nrooms.\nIn order to prevent Negro use\nof public State parks, nine such\nparks have been leased to private\noperators, most of whom had been\nsuperintendents at the parks in\nvolved.\nThe State Patrol and the Geor-.\ns:ia Bureau of Investigation have\nbeen given authority to enter the\njurisdiction of any county or town\nto arrest violators of segregation\nlaws. The legislature also has\ngiven the Governor broad \u201cemer\ngency\" powers similar to the\nFlorida statute.\nLouisiana\nThree of Louisiana's anti\ndc.tfcrcnation laws, written short\nly after the high court's decisions,\nhave been declared unconstitu\ntional in the courts. One was a\nconstitutional amendment de\nsigned to continue segregation\nunder the State's police powers.\nAnother was a pupil-assignment\nplan that provided no criteria for\nassignments. The third was a law\nrequiring all applicants to State\ncolleges to present certificates of\ngood character signed by their\nhigh school principals and district\nschool superintendents. <At the\nsame time, provision was made for\nfiring any school employe w\u2019ho\nperforms \u201cany act\u201d promoting\ninteeration in public schools or\nState colleges.)\nThe State has suspended its\ncompulsory school attendance law,\nand the legislature has adopted\nan interposition resolution. School\nemployes who advocate integra\ntion may be fired. Another law\nrequires white and Negro students\nto be taught only by teachers of\ntheir own race. Other laws are)\ndesigned to make it impossible\nto bring segregation suits against\nthe State school or park systems.\nThe State also requires segre\ngated waiting rooms for intra\nstate narsengers on public car\nriers. In 1956, interracial athletic\nevents were outlawed.\nMississippi\nThe State that most observers\nthink will be the last to integrate\nhas provided for automatic clos\ning of the schools in the event of\nintegration It has also suspended\nits compulsory attendance law,\nand its legislature adopted an\ninterposition resolution.\nThe Governor has appointed\n1.100 lawyers as \"special assistant\nattorneys general\u201d to help defpnd\nanyone against whom a segrega\ntion suit is brought.\nThe legislature set up a State\nSovereignty Commission with al\nmost unlimited powers to prevent\n\"encroachment\u201d by the Federal\nGovernment. The legislature also\nhas directed all officers of the\nState's executive branch to pro\nhibit \u201cthe implementation of or\nthe compliance with\u201d any inte\naratlon order.\nA bill Is now pending that would\nclose schools In the event Federal\ntroops are used to support deseg\nregation.\nAn all-inclusive law makes it\na criminal offense to conspire to i\nviolate segregation laws by force,\nviolence, threats, intimidation or\n\u201cotherwise.\u201d\nSeveral acts of 1956 provide for\nthe designation and use of segre\ngated waiting rooms and rest\nrooms for intrastate travelers.\nNorth Carolina\nNorth Carolina has transferred\nauthority for the enrollment and\nassignment of pupils from the\nState School Board to city and\ncounty boards, thus requiring that\neach of the 172 school districts\nmust be sued In any State-wide\nattack on segregation. But Its\nplacement law, allowing only a\nmodicum of integration, is the\nonly one\u2018that has passed court\ntests.\nAn amendment to the State\nconstitution provides for State tu\nition grants for any pupil whose\nparents do not wish him to attend\nContinued on Pago B-S\nAmusements\nGardens \u2014Music\nTHE WEEK IN PERSPECTIVE\nm\nThe President Writes a Letter\nWhen Winston Churchill made\nhis famous \u201cIron Curtain\u201d speech\nat Fulton. Mo., in 1947, the \u201ccold\nwar\u201d became official; the eco\nnomic, political and spiritual in\ncompatibility of the Communist\nEast and the non-Communist\nWest became a fact of life.\nSince then, the cleavage be\ntween these two \"worlds\u201d attempt\ning to live on one world has been\nwide and deep and often danger\nous. But always there has been a\nhope\u2014sometimes bright, some\ntimes a mere spark\u2014that there\ncould be a meeting of minds, a\ntouching of hands, a civilized com\npromise that would remove the\nthreat of devastating head-on\nmilitary conflict.\nThese hopes flamed brightest\njust before the Geneva \"summit\u201d\nconference in 1955; they faded dis\nhearteningly as the \u201cspirit of\nGeneva\" evaporated. In recent\nmonths they have been fanned\nagain, mostly by a cleverly con\ntrived letter-writing campaign\nconducted by Soviet Premier Bul\nganin. Pen in hand, he has cap\nitalized on the universal desire for\npeace by demanding a new heads\nof-government conference to settle\noutstanding East-West differences.\nCommunist Party boss Khru\nshchev has seconded the motion\non every available occasion.\nIn response, the West\u2014personi\nfied by Secretary of State Dulles\u2014\nhas insisted that a heads-of-state\nsession now would be ill-advised,\nthat careful preparations at a\nlower level must precede any such\nconference\u2014if, indeed, one should\nbe held at all. The Western posi\ntion has been characterized in\nrecent weeks, however, by a slow,\nreluctant acceptance of the fact\nthat some sort of summit meet\ning is inevitable.\nPresidential Letter\nThis was the situation, then,\nlast Monday when President\nEisenhower sent off a reply to Mr\nBulganin's latest missive on the\nsubject of a get-together.\nThe President's bluntly worded\nletter was sprinkled with acid com\nment on the techniques the Rus\nsians have been using, and it took\nissue with Soviet distortions of\nAmerica's policies and motives.\nThrough it there was a \"let\u2019s\nstop this foolishness and get\ndown-to-business\" note that\nseemed to clear the atmosphere a\nbit.\nShunning the ambiguities of\nusual diplomatic communication,\nMr. Eiserhower told Mr. Bul\nganin: \u201cI begin to wonder, Mr.\nChairman, whether we shall get\nanywhere by continuing to write\nspeeches to each other. As I read\nyour successive lengthy missives\non December 10, January 8 and\nFebruary 1, I cannot avoid the\nfeeling that if our two countries\nare to move ahead to the estab\nlishment of better relations, we\nmust find some ways other than\nmere prolongation of repetitive\npublic debate.\u201d\nThe President went on to discus\npoints of differences between the\nSoviet Union and the United\nStates, both in general and speci\nfically on what would be discussed\nat a summit conference if one\nwere to be held.\nThen he made wliat amounted\nto a United States proposal for a\nfirst step toward a summit meet\ning:\n\u201cPerhaps the impasse to which we\nseem to have come can be broken by\nless formal and less publicized contacts\nthrough which we would continue to\nseek to find out whether there can be\na top-level meeting which, in the words\nof my letter to you of January 12, 1958,\nwould hold good hope for advancing the\ncause of peace and justice in the world.\n\u201cExchanges of views effected through\nour Ambassadors or foreign ministers\nmay servo better than what Mr.\nKhrushchev referred to at Minsk os\n\u2018polemics' between heads of govern\nment,\n\u201cThe United States is accordingly\nconsulting with some other interested\nnations as to the desirability of explor\ning, through more normal channels, the\nprospects of a top-level meeting which\nwculd be odeguote as to subjects, and\nas to which preliminary exchanges\nwould indicate good prospect of an ac\ncord. You will understand, of course,\nthat, whatever be She preparatory pro\ncedures, these would, as far as the\nUnited States was concerned require\nthe participation of our Secretary of\nStote.\"\nThe specific reference to the\nSecretary of State was clearly a\npointed rejoinder to the charge\nof \u201cbias\u201d against Mr. Dulles in an\nearlier Bulganin letter.\nAnother high spot of the Eisen\nhower letter was a suggestion that\nthe two nations, so deeply engaged\nin seaiching out the truth about\nouter space, might well set about\nlearning more about each other.\nTo that end. he proposed that\n\u2018leaders of thought and influential\ncitizens within the Soviet Union\u201d\nvisit the United States \"to learn at\nfirst hand the feeling of our peo\nple toward peace and the working\nof our popular institutions as they\naffect our conduct of foreign re\nlations.\"\nThe President commented that\nmost influential Soviet citizens\nappear to have \"totally false con\nceptions\u201d about this country, and\nhe promised that if they were to\ncome here they would receive\n\u201cevery facility to learn about our\ncountry and our people and the\nworking of our political institu\ntions.\"\nIn addition, the President said\nthat present arrangements for the\nexchange of 20 or 30 students a\nyear was a step In the right direc\ntion but \"woefully inadequate,\u201d\nand that Mr. Bulganin might hear\nfrom him further on that subject.\nAll In all, the President's letter\nseemed to go further than most\nflunttatj gifctf\nWASHINGTON, D. C., FEBRUARY 23, 1958\nDEBATE BY MAlL\u2014President Eisenhower responded pointedly Monday to a Bulganin \"summit letter.\"\nsuch documents toward the\nmeeting of minds and the touch\ning of hands that are essential to\nEast-West settlement.\nStill Apart\nThere has been nothing, how\never, in the exchange of mes\nsages to indicate any major\nsoftening of either side's position.\nThe Soviet notes still insisted\nthat talks must be held on the\nbasis of the status quo in Europe,\nwhich means that the division\nof Germany and the Communist\nrule of the nations of Eastern\nand Central Europe must be ac\ncepted by the West. In addition,\nthe Soviet proposals that Ameri\ncan overseas bases be abandoned,\nthat troops be withdrawn from\nEurope, and that an outright ban\nbe effected on nuelear weapons\nhave not been modified.\nAnd on the American side. Mr.\nDulles is continuing to insist\nthat Germany be reunited on the\nbasis of free elections and that\nthe propiss of the satellite na\ntions be allowed to choose their\nown form of government. Obvi\nously. the conditions of each side\nis unacceptable to tfie other. But\ndiplomats are undiscouraged.\nRussia's Mr. Khrushchev has\ncalled for \u201csmall things first\" in\nhis \u201cfirst the appetizer, then the\nsoup, then the main course\u201d re\nmarks a few weeks ago. Now Mr.\nEisenhower takes much the same\nview, at least by implication.\nOut of the cautious communi\ncations between the Soviet Union\nand the West a clearer picture is\nbeginning to take shape. Its out\nlines now seem to suggest that\nG) the Soviet leaders are prob\nably genuinely interested in se\ncuring a cold war \u201ctruce\u201d that\nwill permit them to pay needed\nattention to domestic political and\neconomic problems: (2 that\nworld opinion, added to effective\nif largely silent pressures inside\nthe American administration it\nself, has already neutralized the\nDulles policy of unyielding, un\ncompromising. vigorous opposition\nto any Soviet aims.\nIn the meantime, of course, the\nmore ominous aspects of the cold\nwar continue. It was revealed\nyesterday here in Washington\nthat the United States and Britain\nhave agreed to establish bases\nfor the launching of intermediate\nrange missiles in the British Isles,\nwith the missiles and nuclear\nwarheads to be supplied by the\nUnited States.\nForeign Aid:\nSelling Job\nWhile the men in the Kremlin\nwere studying Mr. Eisenhower s\nreply to Mr. Bulganin, the Presi\ndent moved on another foreign\npolicy front\u2014one of his most\ndifficult. For \"mutual security,\u2019\nthe formal term for what is more\nfamiliarly known as foreign aid\nis as difficult to sell to the United\nStates Congress as the American,\ndisarmament conditions are to\nthe Russians\nTills year, with elections ahead\nand a faltering economy worrying\nthe Nation. Mr. Eisenhower's plea\nfor congressional approval of sub\nstantial economic and military aid\nto friendly nations facea a rougher\nroad than ever. But the President\nfaced the issue: He asked $3 9 bil\nlion for the next fiscal year, and\nwarned that slashes of any magni\ntude could mean \"a beleaguered\nAmerica\u201d alone in a Communist\ndominated world.\nObviously aware of the extent\nof congressional opposition to\nforeign aid, Mr. Elsenhower chose\nto stress the military aspect of the\nMutual Security Act. rather than\nthe economic. But in so doing he\naroused criticism from those con\nvinced that backward economies\ncan be belter helped with agricul\ntural machinery rather than tanks\nind guns.\nAnother keystone of foreign\npolicy facing rough going in Con\ngress is Mr. Elsenhower's request\nfor a five-year extension of the\nReciprocal Trade Agreement Act,\nwhich provides for the progress\nive lowering of trade barriers. Op\nposition, spurred by the recession,\nhas increased to the point that\nmany of the act\u2019s supporters fear\nit many be allowed to did on June\n30. the date on which It Is due\nto expire unless extended.\nLast week House Speaker Sam\nRayburn said, rather darkly, that\nhe did not know whether the act\ncould pass the House this year. It\nis now before the Ways and Means\nCommittee, where protectionists\nhave marshaled their full strength\n\u2014which is considerable\u2014in an ef\nfort to cripple it. if net kill it out\nright.\nMiddle East:\nRatification\nOn Friday a plebiscite held con\ncurrently in Egypt and Syria rati\nfied with a 99 per cent majority\nthe union of the two nations in\nthe United Arab Republic. The\nsame vote approved Gamal Abdel\nNasser as the President of the\nmerged state with almost absolute\npowers. The desert kingdom of Ye\nmen will join the merger this\nweek.\nBut the wild enthusiasm for this\nsignificant step toward realization\nof the ancient dream of Arab\nunity was tempered somewhat by\nreservations as to Col. Najser's\nambitious intentions. Reports\nfrom the Middl- 1 East already in\ndicate a stepping-up of Egyptian\nactivity among nationalist groups\nin Jordan, Iraq and Lebanon. The\nfirst two, joined in a federalizeef\nmonarchy as a counter-measure\nTHE NATIONAL SCENE\nThe Economy: Another Stimulant\nA reduction by the Federal Re\nserve Board in its discount rate\nmeans that the interest rate the\nFederal Reserve System charges\nfor money loaned to member\nbanks is lowered. The bankers\nthen can lower the interest rate\nthey charge individual borrowers.\nTheoretically, at. least, this\nstimulates the economy by in\ncreasing the buying of everything\nfrom appliances to homes. The\nFRB, as an anti-recessionary\nmove, twice in recent months has\ncut Its discount rates, once in No\nvember and again in January.\nBut there is another Reserve\nBoard check on bank lending\u2014\nthe requirement that a specific\npercentage of demand deposits be\nkept in reserve. When a bank has\nloaned up to that point, it can\nloan no more. It can't, that is, un\nless the FRB reduces its reserve\nrequirements.\nThat is the action which the\nFederal Reserve Board took last\nweek. Its reduction in reserve\nrequirements of one half of a per\ncentage point lowered the amount\nthat banks must keep idle in re-\nserve by a half billion dollars. The\neffect of this was to increase the\namount available for lending by\nS 3 billion.\nThe reduction was welcomed in\nfinancial circles, even among those\nwho thought the drop too modest\nto accomplish anything more then\nmeeting the seasonal needs of\nspringtime borrowers\nBeginning next month, there\nwill be an increase in credit de\nmand as a result of tax bills and\nthe normal spring increase in auto\nand home-buying. But much of\nthe newly available credit will be\nused. Government economist*\nhope, to expand business and in\ndustry after current inventories,\nnow being depleted, are removed.\nOther Measures\nIn other anti-recession moves,\nPr< aldent Eisenhower already has\nannounced a modest public works\nprogram as a means of providing\njobs and money, and big defense\ncontracts will be let in the com\ning months to pep up the econ\nomy further.\nHis next broad move against\nthe recession could be a proposal\nfor a tax cut. This will hinge\nlargely on the state of the economy\nand the outlook at the end of the\nto the Egyptian-Syrian union,\nhave long been targets for Col.\nNasser's agents. In Jerusalem. Is\nraelis are looking to their weapons\nand nervously watching the\nbarbed-wire of the armistice line.\nPerhaps because he wished his\nnew United Arab Republic to get\noff to an auspiciqus start last\nweek. Col. Nasser cooled off a hot\nlittle border dispute with Egypt's\nnew ly independent neighbor to the\nSouth\u2014the Sudan. Flaring up\nthreateningly when Egyptian of\nficials began arrangements to con\nduct the unity plebiscite in terri\ntory claimed by the Sudanese,\nhard words set troops moving and\nthe Sudanese brought their com\nplaint to the United Nations.\nThe Security Council, however,\ndeferred action on the complaint\nwhen a conciliatory statement by\nthe Egyptian delegate, Omar\nLoutfl, opened the door to direct\nand amicable negotiations between\nCairo and Khartoum.\nTunisia\nAnother thorny problem for the\nUnited Nations was also in abey\nance last week. Both Tunisia and\nFrance accepted offers of Amer\nican and British \u201cgood offices\u201d to\nsettle the seriously strained rela\ntions following the French bomb\ning of a Tunisian village on Feb\nruary 8\nIn bringing the case against\nFrance to the Security Council,\nTunisia\u2019s President Habib Bour\nguiba had demanded that the\nU. N. consider the Algerian rebel\nlion itself. Since Paris has con\nsistently refused to discuss the\nAlgerian revolt in the interna-\nfirst quarter. March 31. The fig\nures necessary for any tax cut de\ncisions will be ready in April.\nBy then, there also will be some\nindication as to the extent of the\n\u201cinventory recovery\u201d\u2014how fast\nand how far business inventories\nwill have been depleted. If in\nventories are cut back enough, in\ncreased manufacturing activity\nwill be required in order to replace\nthem\nIn the 1949 and 1954 recessions,\nthis was sufficient to return the\neconomy to a healthy level, and\nmanv economists\u2014 includin\" Mr.\nEisenhower\u2019s advisers\u2014are count\ning on inventory recovery to lead\nto a general recovery this time.\nBut in those two declines, in\ndustry was operating at above 90\nper cent of its capacity. Today. :t\nis barely at 80 per cent of capacity\nwhich is giving rise to fears among\nsome economists that rebuilding\nof inventories will not be enough\nto provide the recovery that is\nneeded.\nIn that case, a tax cut. giving\nthe consumer a larger disposable\nincome, might be the wav out.\nIn the meantime, the reces\nsion is threatening to upset Mr.\nEisenhower's 1959 budget, which\nwill not be operative for still an\nother four months. A deficit\u2014\nand a big one\u2014seems inevUable.\nThe $73 9 billion budget\u2014a figure\nthat was accepted rather cyni\ncally in the first place\u2014is certain\nto grow as Congress and the ad\nministration both add to it with\npublic works and defense item*\nRecession also means a smaller\ntax take for Uncle Sam. even\nwithout a tax reduction. And\nwhen income decreases and outgo\nincreases, the deficit fattens.\nMr. Eisenhower twice last week\nassured the Nation that its econ\nomy is still vigorous.\nLast Sunday. James C Hagerty.\npresidential press secretary, re\nported that his chief saw \"an en\ncouraging sign for the economy\"\nin reports showing increases in\nhousing start* and in applications\nfor homebuilding insurance.\nThen on Thursday, the Presi\ndent said, answering fears ex\npressed by 11 Democratic Gover\nnors. that there was no danger of\na \"deep and protracted economic\ndecline\u201d as long as the people have\nconfidence in the economy. And\nhe cautioned again that in fight\nEditorials \u2014Books\nObituaries\ntlonal body, there was once again\na serious threat to the unity of\nthe Western alliance. A United\nStates vote favorable to the Tu\nnisians would be certain to evoka\nFrench wrath and. as in the Suea\ninvasion of 1956, cause dangerous\ncracks in the masonry of the Big\nThree alliance and the North At\nlantic Treaty Organization.\nFrance, severely taxed by the\nbloody and expensive military ef\nfort to suppress the Algerian inde\npendence rebellion, charged open\nTunisian support for the rebels\nand a huge traffic in arms across\nthe Tunisian border. Electrified\nbarbed wire has proved ineffectual\nin halting the movement of aims\nand men across the frontier almost\nat will; now a 15-mile-deep no\nman s land is being created along\n200 miles of the border to check\nthe infiltrations.\nAmerican Deputy Undersecretary\nof State Robert Murphy, named to\nconduct the mediation effort, flew\nto London Friday after talks with\nDag Hammarskjold. U. N. Secre\ntary General. Mr. Murphy, with his\nBritish colleague, Harold Beeley,\nwill try some \u201cquiet diplomacy\u201d in\nParis and Tunis to effect a settle\nment. Meanwhile. Tunisian troops\nare continuing their blockade of\nFrench garrison and of the im\nportant naval base of Bizerte, and\nmost French consulates have been\nordered closed.\nIndonesia:\nViolence\nThe long-gathering revolt\nagainst Indonesia's President Su\nkarno erupted in violence last\nweek. On Sumatra, where re\nsentment against the Javanesa\ndomination of the Indonesian\nfederation was formalized last\nweek in a rebel government, loyal\nist army planes bombed a radio\nstation and a bridge at Patlang,\nJakarta's naval forces were block\nading the Sumatran port.\nRebel grievances stem from\nPresident Sukarno's recent moves\ntoward a \"guided democracy,\u2019*\nwith Communist participation, in\ngoverning the sprawling and\nwealthy archipelago freed from\nDutch rule in 1949. The nation a\nlarge Moslem population, plus a\nhard core of senior army officers,\nmerchants and planters, has op\nposed the Sukarno policy of ad\nmitting Communists to th#\ngovernment desmte their meagra\npolitical strength.\nAn additional source of\nhas been an economic imbalance\namong th- islands, with Sumat\nlans charging huge inequalities m\ntax levies and collections by the\ncentral government.\nPresident Sukarno, who flew\nback to Jakarta Irom a vacation\nin Japan to take personal charga\nof the fight against the rebels,\nblames the United States for en\ncouraging his foes. Secretary\nDulles' remarks at his press con\nference on February 11 that ha\nhoped tor \u201cconstitutional democ\nracy\" in Indonesia brought sharp\nexpressions of annoyance from\nJakarta.\ning the recession \"it is as neces\nsary to avoid doing the wrong\nthing as to do the right one.\u201d\nFCC Hearing:\nInfluence Game\nThe special House Subcom\nmittee on Legislative Oversight,\nits internal bickering subdued,\nturned last week to the task of\ntrying to learn Just how much\nimproper\u2014and possibly illegal\u2014\npressure has been a part of tho\ndecisions of the powerful regu\nlatory agencies that often hold\nthe decision of life or death over\nsome of the Nation's biggest\nbusinesses.\nAt the end of another week of\nhearings, the subcommittee wa#\nconsidering a code of ethics, with\nth<* full force of law behind it\nThese were the highlights of\nthe week's testimony:\nThe groups discharged chief\ncounsel, Bernard Schwartz, at\ntempting to prove his charges of\nWhite House intervention in a\ncase belore one of the agencies,\nr\u00bb leased two letters from Presi\ndential Assistant Sherman Adam*\nto Muiray Cholinei. former cam\npaign manager lor Vice President\nNixon and attorney for North\nAm ncan Airlines. The airline\nat the time .was trying to delay\na Civil Aeronautics Board ruling\nthat ended its status as an \"un\nscheduled\" operator.\nA lawyer for National Airlines,\nwhose subsidiary was seeking a\nlucrative Miami TV license from\nthe Federal Communications\nCommission, testified that he tried\nto approach FCC Commissioner\nRichard Mack through a friend\nof Mr. Mack National s subsio.-\nary later won the channel despite\nan FCC examiner's recommend*!\ntion in behalf es a Miami appli\ncant.\nHie Miumi applicant. Col A.\nFrank Katzmtlne, conceded that\nhe. too. had sought influential\nhelp in the case Tht subcommit\ntee produced a letter indicating\nthat Senator Kefauver was will\ning to talk to FCC member* In\nbehalf of Col. Katzentlne.\nA former Miami Mayor and\nfriend of Commissioner Mack tea-\nContinued on Page B-f\nB","height":"28912","width":"18372"}}
